Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a deep #saucepan{} (with a tight-fitting #lid{}) on medium heat. Once hot, melt in the @butter{20%g}.

Add the onion, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and fry, stirring occasionally, until golden and softened, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Once the onion has softened, add the @sugar{1/2%tsp} and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Stir the @basmati rice{150%g} into the onion until coated in the butter, ~{1%minute}. Add 1/4 tsp salt and the @water for the rice{300%ml}, then bring to the boil.

Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{80%g}, then cut into thirds. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{240%g} and green beans and stir-fry until browned, ~{6-8%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break up the mince as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the garlic, @curry powder mix{1%sachet} and @korma curry paste{50%g} to the beef. Stir-fry until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the @water for the sauce{100%ml} and @chicken stock paste{15%g}. Stir to combine, bring to the boil and simmer until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once the rice is cooked, stir it into the mince and green beans.

Stir through the @mango chutney{40%g}, then remove from the heat.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of water if it's a little dry.

When ready, share the beef pilaf between your #bowls{}.

Drizzle over the @low fat natural yoghurt{75%g} to finish.

Enjoy!